
Engish：General Preface of the Nine Optical Experiments
All optical bright and dark fringes, diffraction and spectral splitting phenomena are formed entirely based on the free diffusion state of light.
The core mechanism of convex lenses (magnifying glasses) and various optical lenses includes expanding the diffusion range, narrowing and converging the diffusion angle. By adjusting the distance, these devices forcibly change the diffusion density and distribution interval of energy packets.
Once the diffusion of light is converged, restricted or forcibly focused, the original dark fringes, diffraction patterns and regional arrangements will fade, blur or even disappear completely.
Whether for slits, obstacles, prism interfaces or thin film structures, their essence lies in boundary constraint and diffusion regulation. All optical phenomena follow a unified rule system of amplification, reduction and diffusion control.
1. Newton’s Prism Dispersion Experiment
Traditional textbook interpretation:
White light is composite light consisting of multiple color components. Different monochromatic lights correspond to different wavelengths. The difference in medium refractive index caused by wavelengths leads to different deflection angles, eventually decomposing white light into a colored spectrum.
Theoretical reconstruction interpretation:
White light is mixed with discrete energy packets of multiple categories and different energy levels. Inside the medium, different types of energy packets are constrained by the grid sea with different strengths, resulting in differentiated deflection angles at the interface.
The core mechanism of dispersion is the classification separation of energy packets and the geometric separation of propagation paths, which has no connection with the hypothetical concept of wavelength.
2. Young’s Double-Slit Experiment
Traditional textbook interpretation:
Light waves produce coherent superposition. Superposed wave crests form bright fringes, while the cancellation of crests and troughs forms dark fringes. Periodic stripes are generated by wave interference.
Theoretical reconstruction interpretation:
The double slit acts purely as a spatial path separator, dividing incident energy packets into multiple independent propagation paths.
Bright fringes are gathering areas where energy packets from multiple paths converge. Dark fringes refer to path prohibition zones restricted by boundaries and grid rules, where energy packets cannot arrive.
Measured data from the Afshar experiment proves that no photons pass through dark areas, directly denying the assumption of energy cancellation and fully supporting the core logic that light and dark distribution are determined by propagation paths.
Interference patterns are only macroscopic statistical projections of the spatial distribution of energy packets.
3. Fresnel Diffraction & Poisson Spot
Traditional textbook interpretation:
Light waves diffract around obstacles. Secondary waves generate superposition and interference, forming a Poisson bright spot at the center of the shadow area.
Theoretical reconstruction interpretation:
Edges of solid obstacles impose mandatory constraints and guiding effects on the moving paths of energy packets. Following valid paths permitted by the grid sea, energy packets detour and converge toward the center of the shadow, forming the central bright spot.
Dark shadow areas are blocked path prohibition zones. The whole diffraction process is the rearrangement of paths under boundary constraints, rather than wave diffusion or superposition.
4. Malus’s Law Polarization Experiment
Traditional textbook interpretation:
Light is defined as transverse wave. Polarizers screen the vibration direction of light waves, and transmitted light intensity changes regularly with the included vibration angle.
Theoretical reconstruction interpretation:
Polarization devices are essentially directional screening equipment for propagation paths. Energy packets have fixed propagation orientations and can only pass through structures with matching directional channels.
Changes in light transmittance only reflect the quantity fluctuation of effective passable energy packets, without any modulation of wave amplitude. Polarization is a direct embodiment of the directional attribute of energy packets.
5. Spectrometer Adjustment and Prism Refractive Index Measurement
Traditional textbook interpretation:
Based on the wave refraction principle, the refractive index is closely related to light wavelength. Optical parameters are calculated through the measured deflection angle of light.
Theoretical reconstruction interpretation:
Different media have distinct density differences in the internal grid sea, which produce different constraining and deflecting effects on energy packets and change their propagation directions.
The physical definition of refractive index is the quantitative index of path deflection of energy packets caused by medium grids. The deflection angle measured by a spectrometer essentially reflects the path curvature change of energy packets during cross-medium propagation.
6. Newton’s Rings Experiment
Traditional textbook interpretation:
Reflected light from the upper and lower surfaces of the thin air film interferes with each other. Optical path difference leads to constructive and destructive interference, forming alternating bright and dark ring patterns.
Theoretical reconstruction interpretation:
The thickness of the air thin film determines the pixel excitation conditions of the local grid sea.
When the film thickness matches the inherent scale range of energy packets, the grid is normally excited to form bright rings.
When the film thickness falls within the forbidden interval of grid gaps, excitation cannot be completed, forming dark rings.
Newton’s rings are typical pixelated projection patterns generated by energy packets and the grid sea. The central dark spot is caused by grid gaps blocking the passage of energy packets, strictly complying with energy conservation and discrete energy rules.
7. Michelson Interferometer Experiment
Traditional textbook interpretation:
Optical path difference is generated between two arms of the optical path. Two beams of light waves superpose and interfere, producing bright and dark fringes and displacement changes.
Theoretical reconstruction interpretation:
The two arms of the interferometer are two completely isolated and independent propagation channels. Energy packets travel separately and then converge.
Alternating light and dark distribution depends on the matching relationship between path length and local grid excitation, with no energy cancellation in the whole process.
Displacement of the reflecting mirror continuously changes the path matching state and drives the overall movement of fringes, belonging to the periodic adjustment of path arrangement.
8. Single-Slit / Grating Diffraction Experiment
Traditional textbook interpretation:
Light waves diffract when passing through narrow slits, and diffraction fringes are formed by the superposition of secondary waves.
Theoretical reconstruction interpretation:
Single slits and grating slits undertake the functions of path screening and spatial shunting. Boundary constraints at structural edges force energy packets to propagate along discrete fixed channels.
Bright fringes are convergence and enrichment areas of multiple paths, while dark fringes belong to path prohibition zones. More grating slits mean higher precision of path screening and denser fringe arrangement.
All diffraction patterns are spatial expansion results of paths restricted by boundary structures.
9. Thin Lens Focal Length Measurement Experiment
Traditional textbook interpretation:
Following the geometric optical refraction principle, the curved surface of the lens refracts light to realize light convergence and imaging.
Theoretical reconstruction interpretation:
The uneven thickness distribution of the lens forms a continuous density gradient of the spatial grid sea.
The thick central area of the lens has stronger grid constraints, continuously bending and converging the paths of energy packets toward the central axis.
The thin edge area presents weak deflection effect.
Focal length refers to the critical distance for energy packets to complete directional convergence. Lens imaging is the physical result of accurate refocusing of scattered energy packet paths.
Supplementary Key Judgment Experiments
Multi-Angle Cross Diffraction Experiment
Superimposed arrangement of multi-directional constraint structures can gradually occupy and cover the originally fixed dark fringe forbidden zones. It directly proves that dark fringes are only limited products of propagation paths, rather than fixed results of wave cancellation.
Magnifier Regulation Experiment behind Double Slit
By installing a convex lens between the double slit and the light screen and precisely adjusting the relative distance of the lens, the original dark fringes can be weakened or eliminated.
If dark fringes are formed by the essential cancellation of light waves, they cannot be artificially erased by adjusting the lens distance. This result directly exposes the core defects of wave theory.
Unified Fundamental Law: Fringes Depend on Free Diffusion
All diffraction and fringe-related optical phenomena can only exist stably when light energy packets are in a free diffusion optical state.
Once the optical path is artificially converged, collimated and restricted to cut off natural diffusion conditions, optical fringes will rapidly fade until they disappear.
This law runs through all nine experiments, being an objective fact that the traditional wave optical system cannot explain self-consistently.
Summary of Inherent Contradictions in Traditional Theory
Single slits have no double-channel structure or superposition conditions, yet they still produce obvious bright and dark fringes.
Double slits and single slits are forced to adopt two different sets of arbitrary "self-interference" explanations, leading to confused definition and double standard rules.
The hypothesis of energy cancellation directly violates the basic law of energy conservation. It is only a temporary mathematical fitting tool without physical reality.
Core Conclusion of Theoretical Unification
The nine classic optical experiments and supplementary judgment experiments can be fully and uniformly explained by a set of underlying logics including energy packets, path separation and grid sea pixel projection, without logical conflicts or forced hypothetical patches.
The settings of constructive and destructive interference as well as energy annihilation in traditional wave optics violate the basic criteria of energy conservation. They are only early mathematical fitting methods and cannot represent the real physical mechanism.
The essential nature of light is discretely moving energy packets. Macroscopic wave characteristics are only superficial appearances derived from path differentiation and natural diffusion, while the discrete particle attribute of light is fundamental.
All optical phenomena including dispersion, diffraction, polarization, interference and imaging are uniformly attributed to three core mechanisms: path selection of energy packets, boundary constraint and grid sea excitation matching.
